Openings d7 and d10 have occurred in strong tournaments despite the proven black advantage in these openings.
In a way, d7 and d10 are quite similar in many cases.
Today however, we will look at d7 only.
As a tradition, we first check some crazy 4th moves, and finally end up with most common ones.
Move 4-i10 is the crazy move of d7 opening.
It cannot transfer to any other opening,
therefore we must study it here.
How about 5th moves? Without knowing any theory most of you will still guess right.

Well, very good all of you.
Possible alternatives are i9 and g8, both very good for black.
Whether there are more possibilities, hard to say.
So we will focus on these three only.
Once, long ago I used to make evaluations to openings in general, I think d7 was graded as 90% or something.
It means, in every branch , the value should be 90-10 in black's favor
ok, the main 5th move, will be too easy
Here, Russian and Japanese theory go on different paths.
Japanese use sharp, open style, with controls.
Russian style is more positional, easier to understand.
By this 7th move, black turns into d11
That is so called Japanese style.
en,this style is easy to understand
Japanese principle is - whatever can be controlled, does not need to be stopped or balanced.
Russians however tend to block everything as long as it does not reduce black's chances.
The benefit of this style is simplicity.
So you can pick your favorite style for yourself.
For that same reason, Japanese do not like 5-g8.
It might be hard to find it in Japanese books for above mentioned reasons.
I think it depends on people's style.

OK, lets see how the variant continues.

because it is not deeply investigated

Move 5-i9 will lead to well known paths, and there are no known bugs.
Well, we only worry about the bug that claims to be black win but in fact may be the opposite.
White cannot attack below because of black's control at j6, see it?
Move i11 is likely made because of absence of direct VCT,
and it brings extra help from right wing.
That additional stone makes both left and right side become winning base.
So, it seems black wins here soon.
